04580nam a22006015i 9780774851947DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748519477 a10.59962/97807748519472doi  a(DE-B1597)662315  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2.S322 2003eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a3231 aSchouls, Tim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShifting Boundaries :bAboriginal Identity, Pluralist Theory, and the Politics of Self-Government /cTim Schouls. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tIdentity Politics and Pluralist Theory -- tApproaches to Aboriginal Identity -- tAboriginal Culture, Nation, and the Politics of Difference -- tAboriginal Women, Youth, and the Priority of Individual Choice -- tAboriginal Boundaries and the Demand for External Equality -- tAboriginal Identity and the Desire for Internal Equality -- tAboriginal Self-Government and the Politics of Pluralism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanada is often called a pluralist state, but few commentators view Aboriginal self-government from the perspective of political pluralism. Instead, Aboriginal identity is framed in terms of cultural and national traits, while self-government is taken to represent an Aboriginal desire to protect those traits. Shifting Boundaries challenges this view, arguing that it fosters a woefully incomplete understanding of the politics of self-government. Taking the position that a relational theory of pluralism offers a more accurate interpretation, Tim Schouls contends that self-government is better understood when an “identification” perspective on Aboriginal identity is adopted instead of a “cultural” or “national” one. He shows that self-government is not about preserving cultural and national differences as goods in and of themselves, but rather is about equalizing current imbalances in power to allow Aboriginal peoples to construct their own identities. In focusing on relational pluralism, Shifting Boundaries adds an important perspective to existing theoretical approaches to Aboriginal self-government. It will appeal to academics, students, and policy analysts interested in Aboriginal governance, cultural studies, political theory, nationalism studies, and constitutional theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralism. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxEthnic identity. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxPolitics and government. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxPolitics and government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485194740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851947/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles